AB  - Our investigation is aimed at the judgement of the dynamic status of vegetation in the secondary succession on mountain landslide in Chiba Prefecture, central Honshu. The permanent plots of A, B and C were set on a slope of landslide based on the stratification of habitat (Fig. 1) and developing vegetation was studied in relation to plant succession. Thus the data on the recovery of vegetation in areas of mountain landslide will be used for the purpose of forest management. 1) In the floristic composition of recovering vegetation (Table 1), the number of species in the first year growth was A>b>c and the increase of the number of species in the second year stage was in proportion to the fiist year stage following the same order. Miscanthus sinensis absolutely dominated in every plot. In the plot C covered by a thick layer of soil, climbing plants, saplings of evergreen broad-leaved tree, etc. are invading. Based on these facts, the fastness in the progression of succession at the permanent plots were C>b>a. 2) The height-growth of the species in the three plots (Fig. 2) indicated that the favorability of habitat to growth was C>b>a as the progression of successional course mentioned above. 3) The life-form composition in each plot shows the recovery of vegetation, too (Figs. 3, 4) and at the same time corresponds to different soil conditions from the standpoint of microhabitat. In the plot A with shallowest layer of soil, characteristics of early stages in secondary succession were shown. In the plot C, the difference among quantities of life-forms decreased, but the diversity of life-forms increased. Such life-form spectra also indicate the fastness in the progression of succession as C>B>A. 4) The tendency in the vegetation recovery in the floristic composition, height-growth and life-form spectra corresponds to the degree of succession (D,S = [(£d-/)/w]-, Table 2). 5) The judgement of vegetation recovery with various measures shows the same order of C>b>a as stated above. Consequently the recovery of vegetation in areas of mountain landslide is most favored where there are physiographic conditions as observed in the plot C. © 1973, THE JAPANESE FORESTRY SOCIETY. All rights reserved.
